metadata.title: Beechcraft Super King Air
aws::graph::propositions: # Beechcraft Super King Air Accommodations and Military Variants
Beechcraft Super King Air accommodations include two pilots above an armored floor.
Beechcraft Super King Air accommodations include a sensor operator console on the port side.
The sensor operator console in the Beechcraft Super King Air faces forward.
The sensor operator console in the Beechcraft Super King Air provides on-board analysis.
Beechcraft Super King Air accommodations include club-four seating in the center section.
Beechcraft Super King Air accommodations include a table on the port side.
Beechcraft Super King Air accommodations include a satellite telephone.
Beechcraft Super King Air accommodations include a refreshment center.
Beechcraft Super King Air accommodations include a lavatory at the rear.
Four Beechcraft King Air 350CERs were originally ordered for the Royal Air Force (RAF).
The Beechcraft King Air 350CERs are designated as Shadow R1 in Royal Air Force service.
The Beechcraft King Air 350CERs are equipped for intelligence, surveillance, target acquisition and reconnaissance (ISTAR) missions.
The Beechcraft King Air 350CERs were equipped for ISTAR missions over Afghanistan.
The Royal Air Force order for Beechcraft King Air 350CERs was increased to six aircraft in July 2013.
Four Beechcraft King Air 350s replaced the Royal Navy's Jetstream T2 observer trainers in 2011.
The Royal Navy's Beechcraft King Air 350s were designated Avenger T1.
On October 3, 2018, the US State Department approved the possible foreign military sale of three Beechcraft King Air 350ERs to the government of Canada.
The estimated cost of the three Beechcraft King Air 350ERs for Canada was US$300 million.
The US$300 million cost of the Beechcraft King Air 350ERs was equivalent to approximately $359 million in 2023.

text:
Accommodations include two pilots above an armored floor; a sensor operator console (port, forward facing) providing on-board analysis; club-four seating in the center section with a port side table; satellite telephone; refreshment center; and a lavatory at the rear.
Four King Air 350CERs (Shadow R1 in RAF service,) equipped for intelligence, surveillance, target acquisition and reconnaissance (ISTAR) missions over Afghanistan, were originally ordered for the RAF. This was later increased to six aircraft in July 2013. Four more King Air 350s replaced the Royal Navy's Jetstream T2 observer trainers in 2011 and were designated Avenger T1.

On October 3, 2018, the US State Department approved the possible foreign military sale of three King Air 350ERs to the government of Canada for an estimated cost of US$300 million (~$359 million in 2023).
